Instead of explaining a solution, I’m going to present a real-world Angular design problem and invite you to solve it. If you’ve built enterprise Angular applications, chances are you’ve encountered something very similar.
The scenario is simple.
Imagine a two-step workflow. The first screen contains a Vehicle Form with three actions in the footer: Discard, Save, and Next. Clicking Next navigates to the Customer screen, where the footer contains only Save and Discard.
Most developers, especially when starting with Angular, would naturally implement something like this.
The Vehicle Component defines its own buttons, with each click handler implemented inside its corresponding TypeScript file.
<h1>Vehicle Component</h1>
<button mat-raised-button color="primary" (click)="discard()">Discard</button>
<button mat-raised-button color="primary" (click)="save()">Save</button>
<button mat-raised-button color="primary" (click)="next()">Next</button><!-- vehicle.component.ts -->
discard() {
console.log('Discard Vehicle');
}
save() {
console.log('Save Vehicle');
}
next() {
console.log('Next Vehicle');
}
